  Category:1412 births Category:1431 deaths Category:British executions Category:Catholic martyrs Category:French military leaders Category:French saints Category:Historical figures portrayed by Shakespeare Category:Hundred Years' War people Category:History of Catholicism in France Category:Natives of Lorraine Category:Nine Worthies Category:People executed by burning at the stake



Joan of Arc's name was written in a variety of ways, particularly prior to the mid-19th century. A few examples are mentioned in Joan of Arc facts and trivia. See Pernoud and Clin, pp. 220–221.↩
Modern biographical summaries often assert a birthdate of January 6. In reality, Joan of Arc did not know her own exact age, and the &quot;January 6&quot; claim is based on only a single source: a letter from Lord Perceval de Boullainvilliers on July 21, 1429 (see Pernoud's Joan of Arc By Herself and Her Witnesses, p. 98: &quot;Boulainvilliers tells of her birth in Domremy, and it is he who gives us an exact date, which may be the true one, saying that she was born on the night of Epiphany, January 6th&quot;). None of the witnesses at her rehabilitation trial provide a birthdate, and the event was probably not recorded. The practice of parish registers for non-noble births did not begin until several generations later.↩
A tribunal led by Inquisitor-General Brehal retried her case after the war. The new verdict overturned the original conviction and described the earlier proceeding as &quot;corruption, cozenage, calumny, fraud and malice&quot;.1 (Accessed 12 February 2006)↩
